==English==
===Etymology===
Greek [[μύθος]] (''mythos''), report, tale, story.

===Noun===
''mythos'' (''plural:'' '''[[mythoi]]''')

# A (fictional) history relevant to a particular character, group, or world. 
# Anything delivered by word of mouth, word, speech, conversation, story, tale, especially the poetic tale.    
# Denotes a tale, story or narrative, usually verbally transmitted, or recorded into the written from an alleged secondary source.  The oppisite of logos, a historic tale which is regarded as verifiable. The narrated events which form a mythic tale are not normally verifiable, their origin is nearly always unknown, and yet they claim to be truth, which the purely fictitious narrative, in forms such as the novel, lacks.

One famous example is Lovecraft's Cthulu Mythos, a series of stories all sharing a single history.

